When the host connects to the website "," the contents of the website finally reach the client in the following steps: The host makes a request to the website, using the appropriate transport-layer protocol (such as TCP or UDP) and port number, requesting the specified web page or resource. The website receives and executes the request, retrieving the requested web page or resource from its server. The website responds to the host with the requested web page or resource, as well as any accompanying data or media. The host gets the answer and analyzes the web page's contents before displaying them on the client device. In summary, the host sends a request to the website using the transport-layer protocol and the proper port number, the website responds with the requested web page or resource, and the host receives and processes the contents of the web page, displaying it on the client device. 